          "body": "Job 34 occupies a structurally unique position in the book. The three friends (Eliphaz, Bildad, Zophar) have made their cycles of argument and been silenced by Job's refusal to confess sin he did not commit; they appear again at 42:7-9 under divine rebuke. Elihu now fills the gap before God speaks from the whirlwind (38:1). This chapter is his most sustained and formal argument — a theodicy, a defense of God's justice constructed without God's assistance. The irony embedded in the book's structure is exquisite: God has already declared in chapters 1-2 that Job is His servant who speaks what is right (1:8; 2:3), yet Elihu constructs a detailed prosecution of Job's speech as wicked (34:35-37). The reader knows what Elihu does not. Reading Job 34 requires holding two frames simultaneously: Elihu's argument as a statement (what he claims about God's justice) and Elihu's argument as a dramatic event (a human being constructing a defense of God that God did not request and may not endorse)."
