          "body": "In the middle of a formal disputation, verse 34:28 introduces a register that is entirely unlike the surrounding material: 'So that they caused the cry of the poor to come to Him, and that He might hear the cry of the afflicted.' This is not abstract theodicy — it is covenant compassion. The wicked rulers God overthrows (34:24-27) are removed precisely because their oppression generates the cry of the vulnerable, and that cry reaches God. The same theology appears in Exodus 3:7 ('I have surely seen the affliction of My people... I have heard their cry'), in Psalm 72:4, 12-14, and in James 5:4 ('the pay of the laborers who mowed your fields, and which has been withheld by you, cries out against you, and the outcry of those who did the harvesting has reached the ears of the Lord of Sabaoth'). Elihu's God is not merely a dispassionate arbiter of cosmic justice; He is moved by the cry of the poor in a way that accelerates His judicial action. This is the chapter's most theologically generative verse — and its most pastorally important."
