          "body": "Verse 34:29 is the chapter's most theologically dense and most frequently overlooked: 'When He keeps quiet, who then can condemn? And when He hides His face, who then can behold Him — that is, in regard to both nation and man?' This is Elihu's answer to Job's specific complaint about divine hiddenness (cf. 23:8-9; 30:20). He does not deny that God is sometimes silent or hidden — he denies that human beings have the standing to render a verdict on that silence. God's quiet is not answerable to us. This asymmetry is genuinely important theology, and it is one of the places where Elihu's argument comes closest to what God Himself will say in chapters 38-41 — not the argument from retributive justice (which the three friends also made and which God rebukes) but the argument from creatureliness: the creature does not have the vantage point to judge the Creator's silences. Calvin in his commentary on Job was alert to this: God's hiddenness is not injustice; it is sovereignty operating at a register above human forensics."
